			<title>[영문] 싱가포르 대법원장 인터뷰</title>
			<description>&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;   &lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/thumb/180/207357.jpg" alt="eng.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;“Courts across the world face similar challenges, including the proliferation of disinformation and misinformation in public discourse (also known as the phenomenon of “truth decay”); the transformative impact of technological advancements, particularly in generative artificial intelligence; and the global access to justice deficit. Against this backdrop, a broader systemic role of the courts has emerged and has assumed increasing importance. … A critical and indeed non-negotiable aspect of this broader systemic role is that courts must endeavour to be accessible to all in order to meet the justice needs of society.”, said the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Singapore, the Honourable the Chief Justice Sundaresh Menon, in an email interview with The Law Times, in light of his visit to South Korea from 11 to 12 March 2025.&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Chief Justice Menon’s remarks reflect a growing global consensus that courts must evolve beyond their traditional adjudicatory functions to serve as active custodians of public trust and inclusion. In an era shaped by technological disruption and the erosion of shared truths, the concept of access to justice is no longer merely aspirational—it is an operational imperative. His comments underscore the need for courts to adopt innovative solutions and engagement strategies that enable all members of society, regardless of background or means, to participate meaningfully in the justice system.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Regarding the recruitment and retention of talent in the judiciary, Chief Justice Menon stated that Singapore’s judiciary has not faced any recent challenges in this area. He agreed with the importance of maintaining competitive remuneration to attract and retain top legal professionals.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Chief Justice Menon also discussed the introduction of the Senior Judge system, implemented through a constitutional amendment in January 2015. He explained that this system allows Singapore to continue leveraging the “collective wisdom of experienced judges” while alleviating judicial workload.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;On the judiciary’s use of artificial intelligence (AI), Chief Justice Menon shared that Singapore is collaborating with Harvey AI to develop an AI-powered platform to assist self-represented persons in cases before the Small Claims Tribunals, valued at up to SGD 30,000. The platform is targeted to be launched by the end of 2025 and, among other things, is expected to assist the parties in the organisation of their materials, the summarisation of documents and submissions, and the presentation of their cases.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Singapore judiciary is committed to their core mission of upholding and strengthening the rule of law. The courts have developed a strong reputation for their swift case processing and digitalised systems, making the justice system highly accessible to both citizens and corporate entities.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Singapore’s reputation for clear and stable laws across corporate, financial, and commercial sectors has also solidified its status as a trusted hub for global companies and investors. The Singapore International Commercial Court (SICC) has also emerged as a leading forum for resolving international commercial disputes, further cementing the country’s position in the global legal landscape.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;In light of these achievements, The Law Times recently conducted an email interview with Chief Justice Menon, who, along with three other justices of the Supreme Court of Singapore, visited South Korea from 11 to 12 March 2025. The interview explored the keys to maintaining high trust and confidence in the judiciary, the structure and personnel management of the Singapore judiciary, and Chief Justice Menon’s perspectives on emerging technologies such as AI in the legal sector.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As Singapore continues to adapt its legal system to meet the challenges of the 21st century, the insights shared by Chief Justice Menon offer a glimpse into the future of one of the world’s most respected judiciaries. Below is the full interview.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- Singapore is rated as one of the jurisdictions with the highest judicial confidence and trust in the world. What do you think are the key factors contributing to this high judicial confidence and trust, and what specific measures does the judiciary take to maintain it?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;“Before I turn to the question directly, I would like to set the stage by addressing an anterior point, which is the role of the judiciary in society today and how that has evolved. The role of the courts was traditionally seen as being limited to the adjudication of disputes. To be sure, that remains the core part of our work. But it is important to recognise that our operating environment has changed fundamentally – courts across the world face similar challenges, including the proliferation of disinformation and misinformation in public discourse (also known as the phenomenon of “truth decay”); the transformative impact of technological advancements, particularly in generative artificial intelligence; and the global access to justice deficit.&lt;br /&gt;Against this backdrop, a broader systemic role of the courts has emerged and has assumed increasing importance. This refers to the institutional responsibility of courts to develop and to operate systems and institutions that can deliver and excel in the administration of justice. A critical and indeed non-negotiable aspect of this broader systemic role is that courts must endeavour to be accessible to all in order to meet the justice needs of society.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;  &lt;br /&gt;It is only by performing both our adjudicative and systemic roles with excellence that we can secure and sustain confidence and trust in our courts. And while I think there are various facets of our work that have contributed to the high levels of confidence and trust in our courts, I will highlight three key factors. These correspond to three distinct stakeholders: our people; members of the public; and court users.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;First, we have sought to ensure that our people – judges, judicial officers and court administrators alike – are competent at what they do, and are persons of character. On competence, one specific measure that we have introduced is to significantly expand our commitment to continuing judicial education and training, not only in core areas of the law, but also in the adjacent areas that are routinely and increasingly encountered by our judges, such as statistics, psychiatry and forensic evidence. To this end, we established the Singapore Judicial College (“SJC”) in 2015, so that we could adopt a coordinated and institutional approach to matters such as curriculum development and pedagogy. And on character, we have developed clear standards of professional ethical conduct for our staff. In particular, we have developed a judicial code of conduct for judges and judicial commissioners which has been made publicly available on our website.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Second, we have invested significantly in our public communications and outreach efforts, in order to ensure that members of the public have a better understanding of our work, and more broadly, the role of the courts in our system of governance. These include measures such as: (i) the publication on our website of all written judgments issued by the Supreme Court, dating back to 2000, accompanied by case summaries of the more significant judgments; (ii) the creation of an official WhatsApp channel to disseminate key messages and notable judgments; and (iii) the launch of a series of “Conversations with the Community”, where, over the course of seven sessions, our judges explored and explained various aspects of our work to the broader community. We believe these measures have helped to enhance the transparency of our work, which is important in helping us to establish and build trust.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Third, in respect of our court users, we have sought to transform our judiciary into a more outward-looking and user-centric one, particularly towards self-represented persons. Central to this transformation has been the establishment of the Access to Justice Division (“A2JD”)  and the Office of Transformation and Innovation (“OTI”). The OTI is working on several important initiatives such as our collaboration with Harvey AI to develop a AI-powered platform for users of the Small Claims Tribunals. As for the A2JD, it has already completed 14 projects since its establishment, with many more in the pipeline. One example is the Digital Guided Questionnaire. Through a series of simple questions, court users are now able to navigate the significant volume of useful information on the judiciary’s website more effectively. Similarly, we have prepared materials, such as short videos, that explain various aspects of the court process in a way that is accessible to lay users. Beyond this, we have also developed simpler procedural frameworks for certain types of cases, in order to promote access to justice. For example, parties in the District Courts can agree to have their disputes adjudicated through a simplified procedure that has been available in the Magistrates’ Courts since 2014. As a final point, I should emphasise the importance of obtaining feedback both from our court staff and from our court users, to allow us to better understand and directly address the issues users face. We have to that end implemented a number of policies, such as by strengthening our channels for public queries, having regular engagements with our users and conducting periodic surveys, and instituting a “no wrong door policy” where court users can make queries at any of our courts, even if the specific query does not strictly speaking fall within the purview of that court. All of these measures have been initiated in recognition of the growing number of self-represented persons who interact with the justice system without the assistance of legal professionals. We must ensure that they too can participate effectively.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;You will note that none of what I have said has happened by chance. Indeed, we do not take the trust that Singaporeans have in our courts for granted. We have come to realise that the need to secure and sustain trust and confidence in our courts is our core mission, especially when there has been a general decline of trust in public institutions in many parts of the world. Yet, we have only been able to achieve this because of our strong collaborative partnerships with the other stakeholders in the justice system, such as the Government, the Law Society of Singapore and the Singapore Academy of Law.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- In recent years, there have been reports of the independence of the judiciary being threatened in some countries. What key measures does the Singapore judiciary take to maintain its independence from external pressures? What do you think are the implications of Singapore’s judicial model for other countries in the global community?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“There are robust institutional safeguards to ensure judicial independence. The tenure and remuneration of Supreme Court Judges are constitutionally protected. Further, to ensure the appointment of competent and impartial judges, the Prime Minister is constitutionally mandated to consult the Chief Justice on the appointment of Supreme Court Judges before he tenders his advice to the President. The President then acts in his own discretion in making judicial appointments. As for the lower judiciary, the appointment, deployment and removal of these judicial officers are subject to the exclusive control of the Judicial Service Commission, which is headed by the Chief Justice.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Beyond institutional safeguards, it is also important to ensure that the public’s perception of judicial independence is maintained, especially in light of the corrosive effects of truth decay. In this regard, to prevent spurious and baseless attacks on the judiciary, we have retained the common law offence of scandalising the judiciary. To be clear, judicial decisions may be criticised fairly, but personal and baseless attacks on individuals or against the institution will not be tolerated.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;On the second part of your question, the reality is that each of our judicial models is shaped by, and operates within, political, historical and social conditions that are unique to each country. That said, the need to implement strong institutional safeguards to maintain judicial independence is perhaps of increasing importance in the light of the phenomenon of truth decay, and the general breakdown of trust in public institutions.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- The Judiciary of Korea has just introduced an upgraded e-litigation system. Please tell us about Singapore’s e-Litigation system. What were the backgrounds of the introduction of e-Litigation?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“eLitigation is actually our second e-filing system. We were among the frontrunners in incorporating technology in the administration of justice, with the introduction of the Electronic Filing System (“EFS”) in 1997. Our second Chief Justice, the late Mr Yong Pung How, was instrumental in establishing this, as part of a wider set of measures that he undertook to modernise our court processes and make them more efficient, so as to clear the significant backlog of cases that our courts faced at that time.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;  &lt;br /&gt;In 2013, we introduced eLitigation which had many improvements over EFS. Notably, as a web-based service, eLitigation eliminated the need for the installation of special software and access by smart cards.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;We are constantly reviewing and enhancing the capabilities of eLitigation, in order to serve our court users well. For instance, the parties are now able to extract draft orders of court that are auto-populated with reference to the relief sought.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- What were the main challenges faced by courts when transitioning to e-Litigation?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The main challenge faced in introducing e-filing was the change management that it called for in relation to judges, lawyers and court administrators. Indeed, when the EFS was first introduced, there were teething issues which resulted in some resistance on the part of the profession and judicial officers. These issues were addressed through active communication and consultation, including a thorough review. Over time, we received the unwavering support of all our stakeholders, and this was pivotal in our journey to modernise and innovate our justice system.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- How does e-Litigation improve the efficiency of Singapore court proceedings?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The introduction of eLitigation has improved the productivity of lawyers and judges, reduced the need to handle large volumes of paper, and removed the need for lawyers and their staff to come to court to file documents. With e-Litigation, lawyers are able to file documents at any time of day, and judges, court administrators, and lawyers are able to access and review documents with ease from their offices or even their homes.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- Since Covid-19, nearly all case conferences are conducted via Zoom (i.e., virtual hearings). As far as I understand, there is a high level of satisfaction amongst parties and legal practitioners. How do you and the Singapore courts view virtual hearings? How have virtual hearings impacted the efficiency of court proceedings in Singapore?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“While we have experimented with remote hearings for a considerable time, the COVID-19 pandemic made it necessary for all stakeholders to embrace remote hearings generally.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;With remote hearings, lawyers and judges are able to minimise the time spent travelling and waiting for their cases to be called. This is particularly valuable for case conferences or matters that are fixed on a bulk list, which typically required lawyers to wait for a considerable amount of time before their matter was heard, and where the hearing itself is typically quite short and often relatively uncomplicated.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;At the same time, we are conscious that remote hearings can reduce the opportunities for lawyers, especially younger lawyers, to develop their advocacy skills and to interact with fellow members of the Bar. Anecdotally, we have also observed that remote hearings can have some impact on court decorum and etiquette.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;And so, while we expect that remote hearings will be a permanent feature of our courts, for some classes of cases, we are shifting toward a more calibrated approach to its use. For instance, in the Court of Appeal and Appellate Division of the High Court, the bulk of the contested and substantive matters are now dealt with by way of a physical hearing, with remote hearings fixed only for matters that involve relatively straightforward issues.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- How do virtual hearings affect the quality of justice in any form or way?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“In our experience, remote hearings do not affect the quality of justice in any form or way. Our main reasons for returning to physical hearings in some cases have to do with our desire to enhance training opportunities and safeguard advocacy standards. Further, in any case, before the matter may be disposed of through a remote hearing, the judge must be satisfied that the interests of justice will not be compromised.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- The Singapore judiciary signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) with Harvey AI, an American legal tech startup backed by Open AI, in 2023, allowing the use of Harvey AI’s artificial intelligence technology. Could you please share the development of a generative AI programme for the Small Claims Tribunals and how has it fared so far? How has this incorporation of generative AI been received well by parties involved and judicial officers?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“We are collaborating with Harvey AI to develop an AI-powered platform to assist self-represented persons (“SRPs”) in the Small Claims Tribunals (“SCT”). By way of background, the SCTs handle more than 10,000 cases a year, with a claim limit of up to S$30,000. The initial demonstrations have been encouraging and we expect to launch the platform later this year.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;We identified cases in the SCT for our pilot, because these are relatively small and routine cases where legal representation is not allowed. We therefore considered that generative AI could go a long way in providing meaningful assistance to SRPs. In particular, our hope is that this platform will help SRPs understand the kind of evidence they need to produce; help them organise their materials and even to present their cases by helping them with the preparation of their submissions; and to summarise the documents and submissions that the other party has filed. Perhaps in time, it may even provide them with a prediction of what is likely to happen and an assessment of their chances of success.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We do not anticipate that there will be resistance to incorporating generative AI in proceedings before the SCT. As mentioned, lawyers are not permitted in such proceedings, and the AI platform is likely to be able to provide real assistance to SRP. It will also be beneficial to our tribunal magistrates. For instance, the platform will be able to provide them with case summaries that can allow them to better examine and digest the evidence and submissions. In that way, we think it will make a real and substantial contribution to enhancing access to justice.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- How do you envision the role of AI in Singapore’s courts evolving beyond the current pilot in the Small Claims Tribunals? What is expected from the incorporation of AI into dispute resolution and judicial system management? How do you see the role of traditional courts evolving with the introduction of advanced legal technology and online dispute resolution systems?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“When we think of AI, there is a tendency to think of AI as a substitute for human judges – the “robot judge” comes to mind. But I suggest that this is not the best way to envision the role of AI in our courts.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;What we should recognise is that the current state of AI is already highly capable, and it can outperform humans in certain legal tasks. Indeed, there is empirical evidence to suggest that some of the legal AI tools available in the market are already more capable than lawyers in summarising documents, analysing court transcripts, extracting data, generating chronologies of key events and facts, and reviewing and analysing documents. I am referring in particular to the report published earlier this year by Vals AI, a US-based company that evaluates AI tools.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;But, despite this, in its present state, it is clear that AI will not be as capable in all the tasks that make up the function of a judge. For instance, AI is likely to be less capable at providing reliable and nuanced judgments about difficult legal issues that require careful and thoughtful application of the law.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;What this means is that while we should adopt a judicious approach to AI, we should be bold about harnessing the benefits of AI in those discrete areas where it can make a real difference, and use it to supplement rather than replace judges.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;In this way, AI holds great promise in addressing two of the most pressing challenges affecting the sustainability of the legal process. The first is complexification, which refers to disputes becoming ever more complex, both from an evidential and technical standpoint. AI has been found to be extremely capable at helping to make sense of and manage vast volumes of information. And the second challenge that AI can help to address is the global access to justice deficit that I mentioned earlier, which is most acute in the context of smaller value disputes involving simpler issues with recurrent fact patterns, and where it would not be economical to engage lawyers. It is in this space that AI has the tremendous potential to help those who need access to justice, by empowering them with practical information and assistance that they would not otherwise have.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;It follows from what I have suggested that traditional courts are here to stay, although technology can and will transform what we do in our courts, and how we do it.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- What measures are being considered to ensure the long-term vitality of the legal profession in the face of rapid technological change?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“We are taking active steps to ensure that our lawyers are able to harness the benefits of AI and that they can continue to add value to their clients. The Singapore Academy of Law and the Law Society are leading the efforts on this front. For instance, in collaboration with Microsoft, the Academy has released a guide and instructional video to provide all lawyers with prompt engineering techniques, in order to help them obtain better results from generative AI tools. This goes towards the fundamental point that AI tools are only as effective as the input they receive. The Academy, also in collaboration with Microsoft, has developed a foundational course on generative AI and prompt engineering.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Beyond this, through the work of a series of committees (the Committee for the Professional Training of Lawyers, the Working Group for the Reform of Legal Education and the Ethics and Professional Standards Committee), we are working towards a much more structured and intentional approach to the way we train young lawyers today, so that our lawyers can continue to thrive. Later in May this year, the Academy will be launching the Junior Lawyers Professional Certification Programme, a specially curated programme that has been designed to help young lawyers develop the practical skills that are necessary in the face of rapid technological change.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- The rising number of cases reaching the highest court, along with the resulting backlog, has always been a critical issue for the Judiciary of Korea. Singapore has dealt with the same issue, and the Appellate Division caught the eyes of the Korean judicial officers. What were the backgrounds of / reasons for the creation and implementation of the AD?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The AD was established in 2021 to address the Court of Appeal’s (“CA”) growing caseload, which had increased both in volume and in complexity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Before the establishment of the AD, all civil and criminal appeals from the High Court were dealt with by the CA. Under the new framework, the CA continues to deal with criminal appeals, but it only deals with prescribed categories of civil appeals, such as appeals relating to constitutional or administrative law, which are likely to have substantial consequences for individuals or society, and appeals involving selected areas of commercial law such as arbitration, insolvency and admiralty law, and appeals from the SICC. The new framework has allowed the CA to focus on key areas and to optimise its resources.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- Since the implementation of the AD, how has it assisted the Judiciary overall? How has the AD impacted the overall efficiency of the Singapore Judiciary? What have been reactions from legal professionals?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;“Over the last four years, the majority of the civil appeals have been dealt with by the AD, and this has eased the hearing load for the CA. Together, the CA and the AD have been able to dispose of matters before both courts expeditiously. The CA also has greater capacity to deal with expedited appeals (such as appeals relating to arbitration and insolvency), and to bring about a speedy resolution of these disputes which are typically time-sensitive. The legal profession has been supportive of the new framework.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- SICC has celebrated its 10th year anniversary. It has been generally well-received by both the judiciary and legal professionals since its establishment in 2015. There appears to be a growing consensus that the SICC is a successful model for international commercial dispute resolution. What were the backgrounds in which SICC was established?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The SICC was established in 2015 to provide a trusted and neutral forum to meet the growing demand for effective court-based international commercial dispute resolution in Asia. The SICC builds on Singapore’s strategic location within Asia, and the reputation of a judiciary that was already well known for its efficiency, competence and integrity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;There were two pressing ideas that drove its establishment – first, the recognition that the explosive growth in commercial activity in Asia will inevitably be accompanied by an increase in cross-border commercial disputes; and second, the desire to enhance Singapore’s status as a leading international dispute resolution hub, by developing an entire suite of dispute resolution services for commercial parties to resolve their disputes, including litigation, arbitration and mediation.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- How does it help enhance Singapore’s position as an international dispute resolution hub?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The SICC enhances Singapore’s position as an international dispute resolution hub by offering a mode of dispute resolution that is thoroughly international in outlook and in practice. I will highlight a number of notable features that distinguish it from domestic courts:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;a.	A diverse panel of eminent and experienced international and local jurists from both civil law and common law jurisdictions.&lt;br /&gt;b.	The adoption of international best practices for commercial disputes, that combine the best practices in litigation and arbitration, as well as across both the common law and civil law traditions. &lt;br /&gt;c.	Flexible procedures which may be tailored to suit the parties’ preferences. The SICC has its own set of specialised procedural rules that are optimised for the resolution of complex international commercial disputes.&lt;br /&gt;d.	A much more open approach to foreign legal representation. Parties can be represented by foreign lawyers registered with the SICC in certain circumstances.&lt;br /&gt;e.	A costs regime which allows the successful party to recover virtually all its reasonable costs. This is distinct from the approach adopted in the General Division of the High Court, which deals with the majority of the civil matters filed in the Supreme Court. &lt;br /&gt;f.	A system of close, early and continuous judge-led case management, to ensure the just, expeditious and economical disposal of cases.&lt;br /&gt;g.	The SICC also retains the advantages of litigation such as the availability of an appeal mechanism; proceedings in open court; and the ability to join third and related parties in appropriate circumstances.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- With more than 20 international judges, how does the Singapore judiciary maintain the capacity and capability of SICC?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“To ensure that the SICC Bench remains of the highest calibre, International Judges are selected and appointed through a careful and thoughtful process. The SICC seeks to appoint international judges based on their distinguished credentials, extensive experience in commercial law, and expertise in different legal traditions, to meet the evolving needs of international business and to navigate complex transnational disputes effectively.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;In the course of their work, the Judges are supported by the registrars in the SICC Registry, the law clerks and our court administrators.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- How do you see the role of international judges in the Singapore International Commercial Court developing in the coming years?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“Above all, because we have drawn upon some of the finest commercial judges to work with our own judges, I think our combined pool of judges will be well placed to address some of the most challenging issues in international commercial disputes through our jurisprudence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;But, in line with the evolving role of the judiciary, I see our International Judges also playing a greater role in our non-adjudicatory work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;First, by virtue of their experience and expertise, International Judges can be a rich source of ideas and perspectives in promoting systemic reform. In fact, many of the initiatives that have already been introduced by the SICC have originated from the suggestions of our International Judges, or were developed in close consultation with them.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Second, International Judges can serve as ambassadors of the SICC through their participation and thought leadership in international engagements, including those that showcase the work of the court. To that end, we recently organised a public conference to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the SICC. It was very well attended and featured a superb lineup of moderators and speakers, many of whom flew in from all across the world, including from the Republic of Korea. We will also be publishing a commemorative book on the SICC later this year, featuring many of our International Judges as co-authors.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- Do you see any relationship between the SICC and the growing demand for international arbitration?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“International arbitration does not exist in a vacuum, and the growing demand for international arbitration has created a demand for supervisory courts that hear and effectively deal with matters arising from them, such as challenges to arbitral awards.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Such supervisory courts should be able to resolve the disputes that come before them effectively, efficiently and in a commercially sophisticated manner, and the SICC is well equipped to perform this role. In particular, the SICC is committed to managing challenges to arbitral awards promptly. When a challenge is filed, the aim is to dispose of it within six months at first instance, and within a further six months if an appeal is filed. Where the supervisory court in a seat jurisdiction has an excellent understanding of arbitration and a sound appreciation of the collaborative relationship between arbitration and the courts, it can play a vital role in helping the arbitration ecosystem flourish and grow.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- What initiatives are being considered to enhance cross-border judicial cooperation, particularly in light of the increase in international commercial disputes?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“A notable initiative in the past year was the establishment of the International Committee of the SICC, a standalone body to hear appeals and related proceedings from prescribed foreign jurisdictions. The members of the International Committee will include permanent members drawn from the Judges and International Judges of the Supreme Court of Singapore, and ad hoc members drawn from the court of the foreign jurisdiction that is referring an appeal to the International Committee. The International Committee will provide a transnational appeal mechanism that promotes the coherent development of a sophisticated body of transnational commercial law.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;The catalyst for the establishment of the International Committee was the signing of a bilateral treaty between the Governments of Singapore and the Kingdom of Bahrain in March 2024 to establish the Bahrain International Commercial Court (“BICC”), which will be modelled after the SICC. Appeals from the BICC may be heard by the International Committee. We are cooperating with Bahrain in various areas, including in judicial training, devising the relevant legal framework, and developing best practices to effectively adjudicate international commercial disputes. Through such cooperation, we hope to enhance the role that international commercial courts can play in upholding and strengthening the rule of law and the international rules-based order. In time to come, we hope to cooperate and collaborate with other like-minded partners, and help shape the future of transnational commercial justice.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Beyond this, we also collaborate and cooperate with other jurisdictions to promote the efficient and effective resolution of international commercial disputes, such as by entering into memorandum of guidance on the enforcement of money judgments (with countries such as China and Qatar), and on references of questions of law (with foreign courts such as the Supreme Court of New South Wales and the Dubai International Financial Centre Courts).”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- The Judiciary of Korea has been dealing with a “so-called” brain-drain issue. A large number of capable and experienced judges have left for private practice. Reasons vary, among which is less competitive compensation for judicial officers. Has the Singapore judiciary ever faced the same issue?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The Singapore judiciary has not had to deal with the issue of “brain drain” in the recent past. In respect of our judicial officers (the junior judiciary), attrition is well within industry and public sector norms, and there is steady interest from the private sector to join the judicial service.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- What efforts are in place to retain the best talent for the Judiciary? How much does keeping a competitive compensation level for judicial officers of Singapore including judges help retain the best talent?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The starting point is that we are committed to recruiting and retaining Judicial Service Officers (“JSOs”) of ability and integrity, and who are committed to administering justice.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Therefore, we invest considerable efforts to recruit our fair share of the best and brightest talent in the legal profession, including from among fresh graduates to serve in the Justices’ Law Clerk Programme, and to staff positions within the judiciary.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Keeping a competitive compensation level for our JSOs is important in helping us attract and retain talent, and we work closely with the Government on this. We conduct annual remuneration reviews to ensure that salaries are competitive, especially in the early years of their career. The approach that we adopt is to uphold a fair reward and recognition system that keeps pace with, but does not lead, the private sector. This is particularly crucial for our younger officers who are embarking on their careers and who have no lack of options in the private sector. We do recognise that at a certain stage, there will be a marked disparity between the compensation in the public service and that received by the top private practitioners. But we do hope that by that time, we would have developed and nurtured officers with a strong sense of public ethos and who derive great meaning and purpose from what they do, and who therefore will be prepared to stay the course.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;    &lt;br /&gt;At the more senior levels, we are able to attract some of the leading practitioners to come to the senior judiciary even if it means taking a cut in compensation. These individuals are willing to do this because the public service is seen as a prestigious avenue which gives them an opportunity to serve the nation which has afforded its citizens so much. Also, even though they may take a significant reduction, the compensation remains fair.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;Finally, I believe the judiciary will be able to attract and retain its fair share of talent as long as it remains a trusted and respected national institution; and as long as there are robust measures in place to train and develop our people to enable them to maximise their potential.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- Additionally, losing expertise is another issue. Singapore’s Senior Judge system may be a solution to this issue. Why was it introduced against what backgrounds?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“Our Supreme Court Judges are drawn from outstanding members of the legal profession who have distinguished themselves in the private or public sector or in academia. As Singapore has a relatively small legal profession, the pool of talent with the requisite quality and attributes to become Supreme Court Judges is correspondingly even smaller.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Against this backdrop, we introduced the Senior Judge scheme in January 2015 to allow the judiciary to continue to tap the experience and expertise of retired Supreme Court Judges. Many of these Judges are still in very good health, have a wealth of judicial experience and are keen to continue to contribute to the work of the judiciary. The Senior Judge scheme enables them to do so but at a slower pace and with greater flexibility in scheduling based on their availability.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- How does it help the Singapore judiciary?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Senior Judges may be appointed to hear cases in the High Court, the Singapore International Commercial Court or the Court of Appeal. They help relieve the caseload of the Supreme Court Judiciary by contributing to the disposal of cases.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;The Senior Judge scheme also allows the court registry to fix hearings of applications on short notice, with Senior Judges being rostered as Duty Judges to hear urgent applications such as injunctions. This minimises disruptions to the hearings of other Supreme Court Judges.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Through the Senior Judge scheme, we retain the collective wisdom of experienced judges but at the same time we are able to renew the Supreme Court Bench by appointing younger judges to the permanent establishment.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- Please share with us a prominent example of a Senior Judge.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“There are currently 5 Senior Judges on the Supreme Court Bench, all of whom have had distinguished careers in the law. For example, Senior Judge Andrew Phang, formerly the Vice-President of the Court of Appeal, is widely regarded as a legal giant in the common law world, particularly in the field of contract law. Over the course of 23 years as an academic lawyer, and 18 years as a judge, he authored more than 260 academic publications and around 400 judgments, many of which have been cited by foreign courts and scholars. (see “Valedictory Reference Convened to Honour Justice Andrew Phang”)”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;- Singapore has significantly updated the Family Justice Rules, aiming to streamline divorce and separation processes, reduce delays, and promote a solution-focused approach. One of the new policies that has gained attention is the introduction of the Simplified Uncontested Divorce, also known as the Simplified Track Divorce. Why the changes? What are the policy objects to achieve? What are the benefits expected of these new procedures? How have they been received by parties and legal practitioners? How might the ‘Therapeutic Justice Model’ in family justice be expanded to other areas of law in Singapore?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“The overarching philosophy in our family justice system today is what we refer to as Therapeutic Justice. This is a model of justice that tries to promote therapeutic outcomes. We believe that family breakdown is an extremely distressing experience and the legal process should be designed to minimise the adverse consequences such as acrimony and dysfunction, and maximise the prospects of recovery by focusing on the parties’ shared interests, especially those of their children. We also try to ensure that the process is as accessible as possible, especially for self-represented persons who form a significant component of our users in the Family Justice Courts.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;To this end, a new set of Family Justice Rules came into effect in October 2024, representing a complete overhaul of the procedural regime governing family cases. The new rules have been simplified to enhance accessibility for self-represented persons, and they also seek to strengthen the judge-led approach we take in family proceedings, by equipping our judges with, and facilitating the exercise of, a wider range of powers, such as summarily making orders to protect the welfare of the child even without a formal application, or disallowing the filing of further applications or documents. These powers ensure that cases can be resolved with less acrimony, cost and time.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Simplified Track for divorce proceedings, which you have referred to, was introduced almost a decade ago in 2015. The intent was to provide a far quicker and less costly process for divorce proceedings, for parties who are able to agree on all the issues relating to the divorce and the ancillary matters. We hoped that this would encourage them to reach a mutual agreement on the various issues that arise in a divorce and which are invariably issues of a very personal nature that really ought to be resolved by the parties themselves. The Simplified Track has been a tremendous success – while only 24% of cases were filed on the Simplified Track when it was first launched, that figure rose to 63% in 2024. In the light of its success, the Simplified Track was expanded in October 2024 to include judicial separation proceedings, as well as cases where the parties only agree on the divorce or judicial separation, but not on the ancillary matters.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;On the expansion of the Therapeutic Justice Model (“TJ Model”) to other areas of the law, I have suggested in a recent article (see “A New Perspective on Climate Disputes: Lessons from Therapeutic Justice“) that one area that might be suitable is that of climate disputes. In particular, the following features of Therapeutic Justice – its judge-led approach; the integration of multidisciplinary expertise into court processes; and the prominent role of alternative dispute resolution – appear to be particularly apt for the resolution of climate disputes. And within the field of family law, we are also exploring the expansion of the TJ Model to other areas such as probate matters and Youth Court cases.”&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;- As Chief Justice, what do you envision the ideal judiciary of the future to look like?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“I mentioned earlier the series of ‘Conversations with the Community’ that we organised. Over the course of two speeches, I spoke about the evolving role of the courts in society and the need for a refreshed conception of the rule of law. Those two speeches set out a vision for what I see as the judiciary of the future, and in many ways, these have already been mentioned in my responses to your earlier questions – among others, the need to ensure that the justice system is accessible to all; the critical importance of embracing technology to improve the efficiency of court processes and enhance access to justice; and the need to reconsider the appropriateness of traditional adversarial processes in certain areas of the law.&lt;br /&gt;But I wish to focus on a point which I have not touched on in this interview, and that is the need for judiciaries to engage and to collaborate with one another. We can take this at two levels. To begin with, there are certain types of cases where there is a real need for judiciaries to work together so as to ensure that a just result can be reached. I have in mind disputes which have an international dimension and where there are “live” issues that can be resolved much more effectively if there are open channels of communication between judiciaries. The Judicial Insolvency Network is an excellent example of this, in the context of cross-border insolvency; and so too is the International Hague Network of Judges for transnational family disputes.&lt;br /&gt;But beyond this, there are also challenges that affect all of humanity and which therefore will inevitably come before our courts as live issues, or affect the work that we do. The former would include disputes relating to climate change and artificial intelligence, while the latter would include challenges such as truth decay and the breakdown of trust in public institutions.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;Against this backdrop, there is so much that we can learn from one another and by engaging in open and honest discussions. That brings me to my inaugural visit to the Supreme Court of Korea. Over the course of two days, we were hosted by the Honourable Chief Justice Jo Hee-de and his team, and we are deeply grateful for the outstanding hospitality that they extended to us. We had an engaging and excellent bilateral session with the Supreme Court, and we also visited other key institutions in the Korean Judiciary, such as the Seoul Bankruptcy Court, the Judicial Policy Research Institute, the Judicial Research and Training Institute, the Supreme Court IT Centre and the IP High Court. We learned so much from our short time here and we very much look forward to deepening our warm friendship with the Korean Judiciary.”&lt;/p&gt;</description>
